ce:section.ce:para:
After the successful preparation of FCQD, we planned to investigate whether a stable inclusion complex can be formed between the synthesized FCQD and CD. CDs having unique cup-shaped structure are composed of D-glucose units linked with α-1,4-glycosidic bonds [43,44]. Stereochemical arrangement of the cavity present in CD implies that its interior is hydrophobic, while the exterior is hydrophilic [45,46]. Thus, the 3D inert cavity of CD can act as host for hydrophobic guest molecules [45,46]. The carbon core of FCQD derived from citric acid contains hydrophobic aromatic groups [22], which may behave as suitable guest molecule to ‘host’ CD. Moreover, the size of some synthesized FCQDs might have quite compatibility with the cavity size of βCD i.e. ∼0.7 nm. Thus, we chose βCD as host molecule. In order to form the inclusion complex of βCD and FCQD, an aqueous solution having 1:1 wt ratio (w/w) of βCD and FCQD was prepared. This solution was dialyzed to remove free βCD and the UV-visible spectrum of the dialyzed solution was recorded in reference to βCD (Fig. 2b). The absorbance spectra of βCD showed λ
                        max at 273 nm, which blue-shifted to 277 nm in case of the mixed solution of βCD and FCQD indicating the change in surface property of βCD due to the formation of βCD-FCQD inclusion complex. A UV titration of FCQD into βCD was then performed to measure the binding constant (KB) between βCD and FCQD (Fig. 3
                        ). The KB value was found to be 1.78 × 10−3 mL/μg, which indicates sufficient stability of βCD-FCQD inclusion complex.
